<p>Exercise 1</p>
<ol type="1">
<li class="row1">
<p>
If using your Linux VM, create directory <b>lab08</b> under your
<b>/var/www/labs</b> directory, if it does not exist.
Otherwise create directory <b>lab08</b> under
the document root of whatever web server you are using. On the MATC Windows lab
computers, using XAMPP on your external drive that will likely be:
<b>E:\xampp\htdocs</b> or <b>F:\xampp\htdocs</b>
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Download the HTML form <a href="stickyForm.php.txt">stickyForm.php</a> from the
Blackboard version of this lab, into your lab08 folder. Open it in a text editor
and save it as <b>lab8x2.php</b> . Look over the code to see how the "sticky"
form functionality is programmed.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Add 4 additional fields to the form:
</p>
<ul>
<li>streetadr - to hold the user's street address</li>
<li>city - to hold the user's city</li>
<li>state - to hold the 2 character state abbreviation</li>
<li>zipcode - to hold a 5 or 9 digit zip code</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
The 4 new fields should be "sticky", just like <b>name</b> and <b>phone</b> . If
the user has entered valid data into the field, but not all fields pass validation,
the form should be redisplayed with appropriate error messages.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>
Modify <b>lab8x2.php</b> so that, when all fields pass validation, it displays
complete user information (name, phone, streetadr, city, state, zipcode) and
then exits, instead of displaying:</p>
<blockquote><code>
OK! Go ahead and Process the form!<br>
</code></blockquote>
<p>
as it currently does.
</p>
</li>
<li class="row1">
<p>Test your code and show it to your instructor.</p>
</li>
